AB  - The influence of water temperature (17 and 25 degreesC) and a period of fasting on the self-selection of macronutrients were examined in common carp held on a 12:12-h light/dark cycle. Eight replicate groups of juvenile carp (ca. 15 g body weight at 17 degreesC and 25 g at 25 degreesC) were fed with three test diets [high-protein (HP), high-fat (HF) and high-carbohydrate (HC) diets] by individual self-feeders for 3 weeks, followed by a 2-week period of fasting and then 3 weeks of refeeding. At 17 degreesC, the carp initially selected the HP and HF diets [HP/HF/HC (%) = 3 8:40:22], whereas at 25 degreesC, the carp selected the HP diet over the others (55:21:24). After fasting, the carp tended to increase their demand for the HF diet at 17 degreesC and for the HC diet at 25 degreesC, but the overall self-selection of the test diets did not differ markedly from that prior to fasting. Carp held at 17 degreesC had higher relative whole body fat content and plasma triglyceride concentration; the latter decreased markedly during fasting. These results suggest that water temperature influences the macronutrient selection by carp: a relatively high demand for both protein and fat at 17 degreesC and for protein at 25 degreesC. Two weeks of fasting, however, did not markedly alter their macronutrient selection. (C) 2003 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved.
