AB  - The currently rising sea temperatures are expected to affect the structure of aquatic communities. Through increased metabolic rates, activity and feeding motivation, higher temperature can be expected to add to competition and predation risk for many small fish and juveniles. However, behavioural flexibility e.g. individual variation in the expression of behavioural traits may act to buffer the detrimental effects of increased temperature. In the present study we ask how juvenile Atlantic cod respond to food availability and predation risk at the limits of their current natural temperature at the Icelandic coast (3 degrees C-13 degrees C). At 13 degrees C Atlantic cod juveniles responded less to risk, remaining active, dispersed and leaving shelter positions earlier. However, at the same time their feeding attempts reduce significantly and correspondingly to the lower temperature. Therefore, our results suggest that at 13 degrees C Atlantic cod juveniles do not adjust their behaviour to manage the increased feeding motivation while under risk. However, we do find evidence for individual variation in how behaviour is expressed across treatments indicating natural variation that could respond to selection. In conclusion, our results suggest that increased sea temperature could have both immediate negative effects on survival and initiate a selective response in Atlantic cod populations. (C) 2011 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.
